{"sequence":55,"timestamp":"2026-04-18T15:18:06.963604318Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-c080752f","body":"finding_summary: The new BR adapter suite never exercises the dependency mutation entry points, so one of the bead's explicit scope items (nominal dependency operations) is still unverified.\nseverity: low\naffected_files:\n- tests/unit/br_adapter_test.rs\n- src/adapters/br_process.rs\nevidence:\n- src/adapters/br_process.rs:1410-1445 contains `add_dependency`, `add_dependency_with_kind`, and `remove_dependency`, each with their own command construction and tracked-mutation/journaling path.\n- tests/unit/br_adapter_test.rs:281-328 covers only `dep tree` read parsing, and tests/unit/br_adapter_test.rs:360-570 moves on to create/update/close/sync without any add/remove dependency mutation test.\nimpact: A regression in `dep add`, `dep add --type=parent-child`, or `dep remove` would miss the new mocked unit coverage even though the bead scope calls out nominal dependency operations.\nremediation_hint: Add at least one happy-path dependency mutation test, and preferably one explicit parent-child kind case, asserting both the command line and pending-mutation journal behavior.","dedup_key":"48cff3a0a1999f63fd0c82c9f20651091a5841aaeda932207a9d6019baa327d5","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260418140316","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":56,"timestamp":"2026-04-18T15:18:06.972095783Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-3069b6de","body":"`bv_empty_graph_reports_no_next_bead_gracefully` (tests/unit/bv_adapter_test.rs:213-245) and `bv_blocked_graph_reports_all_beads_blocked` (tests/unit/bv_adapter_test.rs:247-280) are byte-for-byte duplicates. Both scripts return the exact same payload `{\"message\":\"No actionable items available\"}`, both assert `BvParseError` with identical `raw_output`, `command`, and error-branch structure, and both exercise the same `--robot-next` path. The bead scope explicitly called out these as two distinct scenarios (empty graph vs. fully blocked graph). As written, the second test adds no differential coverage over the first — one test produces the same signal, and running both inflates the count without adding a verifiable invariant.\n\nFix: either give the two tests genuinely different scripted inputs that distinguish the scenarios (for example, a completely empty JSON object for empty-graph and a payload that explicitly enumerates blocked bead IDs / returns `{\"message\":\"All beads blocked\",\"blocked\":[...]}` for the all-blocked case) and adjust the assertions to match each real bv payload shape, or collapse the pair into a single parameterized test covering both call sites with clearly separate inputs. Either approach keeps the bead's requested scenario coverage honest.","dedup_key":"b79a147c2ad5ce3914b530144a6e90a592b9cca4ce679ba92771a1840c8dd010","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"claude","model_id":"claude-opus-4-7-max","reviewer_id":"reviewer-2"}],"run_id":"run-20260418140316","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
